ners in Oakland, California, and another in Guadalajara, Mexico, Palacios reveals parallels—and contrasts—in the ways these ordinary Catholics receive and act on a church doctrine that emphasizes social justice. Whether they are building a supermarket for the low-income elderly or waging protests to promote school reform, these parishioners provide important insights into the construction of the Catholic social imagination. Throughout, Palacios also offers important new cultural and sociological interpretations of Catholic doctrine on issues such as poverty, civil and human rights, political participation, and the natural law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristian sociologyxCatholic Church. 0aChristian sociologyxMexico. 0aChristian sociologyzMexico. 0aChristian sociologyzUnited States. 0aChurch and statezMexico. 0aChurch and statezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acatholicism, religion, spirituality, activism, mexico, social justice, faith, devotion, community, doctrine, guadalajara, california, oakland, protest, charity, outreach, sociology, natural law, political participation, human rights, poverty, christianity, church and state, roman catholics, mission, public engagement, influence, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022664500140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226645025423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226645025/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles